player.comments_unclear: The final payment calculation was very complicated. It made me feel like the decision has already been made in advance, that the payment will be according to Task 2, because it's easier to program that than to program paying for Task 1.    Also, I don't think I was actually matched to two other people in a group in Task 1 or to another randomly chosen person in Task 2. That it was just made for us to believe, because who's going to program all of that into the program when just making us believe that it happened is enough?
player.reasons_effort_general: I opened a new Google Sheets document, and tried to calculate the expected pay-off and variance. The ratio of the former to the latter would give me the "risk". But I didn't have enough time to code everything in, so I just looked for which one gave me more expected pay-off if I were the leader (risk-neutral).    For predicting what the leader chose, it was easy to go with Investment X probability 0 for the 250-50 and 200-0 case. For the 300-50 case, I didn't know how risk neutral the leader would be, so I had to make a gut decision there. I thought many people are more risk-averse than I am in these kinds of experiments, so I went with a gut feeling of 70%. The ideal way would be to calculate the Sharpe ratio/"risk" (expected payoff divided by variance or std deviation) and use their ratio to determine the percentage, but I didn't have time to calculate and implement that in my Google Sheets.     For predicting what the leader chose given that the investment has succeeded or given that the experiment has failed, I wanted to use Bayes' formula, but I couldn't calculate it in time, so I just did 75% * probability that I think investment X was chosen + 25% * probability that I think investment Y was chosen for part 2(a) and switch 75% and 25% for part 2(b)
